\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Euclidean Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this article, let 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{N}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Euclidean Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is the prototype of all manifolds.
 Not only is it the simplest, but locally every manifold looks like 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A good understanding of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is essential in generalizing differential and integral calculus to a manifold.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A real-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 if its partial derivatives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\partial_{x_{i_{2}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{j}}}f
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
of all orders 
\begin_inset Formula $j\leq k$
\end_inset

 exist and are continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 A vector-valued function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if all of its component functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if it is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 A similar defintion holds for a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We treat the terms 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as synonymous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a continuous function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The polynomial, sine, cosine, and exponential functions on the real line
 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(x)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{3}x^{-2/3} & \mbox{for }x\neq0\\
\mbox{undefined} & \mbox{for }x=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Thus the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\in\mathbb{R}\mid x\neq0\}\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{x}f(t)dt=\int_{0}^{x}t^{1/3}dt=\frac{3}{4}x^{4/3}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(x)=f(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 In the same way one can construct a function that is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k+1}$
\end_inset

 at a given point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is smooth and even bijective with inverse 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is not smooth, as shown above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Continuity of a function can often be seen by inspection, but the smoothness
 of a function always requires a formula.
 The graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x^{5/3}$
\end_inset

 looks perfectly smooth, but it is in fact not smooth at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, since its second derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $y''=(10/9)x^{-1/3}$
\end_inset

 is not defined there.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the norm function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by sending 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=\sqrt{x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We will do this in detail.
 First we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 We prove this by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is trivial: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}\left(\|x\|\right)=\frac{x_{n}}{\|x\|}
\]

\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{x_{n}}^{k+1}\left(\|x\|\right) & =\partial_{x_{n}}\left(\frac{f(x)}{\|x\|^{2k-1}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(x)}{\|x\|^{2k-1}}+\frac{(1-2n)x_{n}f(x)}{\|x\|^{2k+1}}\\
 & =\frac{(\partial_{x_{1}}f)(x)\left(x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}\right)+(1-2n)x_{n}f(x)}{\|x\|^{2n+1}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This establishes our claim.
 Now given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{1}}^{k_{1}}\cdots\partial_{x_{n}}^{k_{n}}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)/\|x\|^{2(k_{1}+\cdots+k_{n})-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial (just use the same induction proof).
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, we see that the norm function is smooth in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{\mathbf{0}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be smooth.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f=\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is smooth.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We will only sketch the proof here.
 By the chain rule, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}(g\circ f)=(g'\circ f)\cdot\partial_{x_{n}}f
\]

\end_inset

By the product rule we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}(g\circ f)=(g''\circ f)\cdot(\partial_{x_{n}}f)^{2}+(g'\circ f)\cdot\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}f
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}^{3}(g\circ f)=(g'''\circ f)(\partial_{x_{n}}f)^{3}+3(g''\circ f)(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(\partial_{x_{n}}^{2}f)+(g'\circ f)\partial_{x_{n}}^{3}f.
\]

\end_inset

More generally, we will have a pattern which involves stirling numbers.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
neighborhood
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is an open set containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
real-analytic
\series default
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if in some neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 it is equal to its Taylor series at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)(x_{i}-p_{i})+\frac{1}{2!}\sum_{i,j}\partial_{x_{i}}\partial_{x_{j}}f(p)(x_{i}-p_{i})(x_{j}-p_{j})+\cdots+\frac{1}{k!}\sum_{i_{1},\dots,i_{k}}\partial_{x_{i_{1}}}\cdots\partial_{x_{i_{k}}}f(p)(x_{i_{1}}-p_{i_{1}})\cdots(x_{i_{k}}-p_{i_{k}})+\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

A real-analytic function is necessarily 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, because as one learns in real analysis, a convergent power series can
 be differentiated term by term in its region of convergence.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\sin x=x-\frac{1}{3!}x^{3}+\frac{1}{5!}x^{5}-\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
then term-by-term differentiation gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(x)=\cos x=1-\frac{1}{2!}x^{2}-\frac{1}{4!}x^{4}-\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The following example shows that a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function need not be real-analytic.
 The idea is to construct a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 whose graph, though not horizontal, is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

very flat
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 near 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in the sense that all of its derivatives vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{smoothnotanalytic}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (A 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function very flat at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

).
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
e^{-1/x} & \mbox{for }x>0\\
0 & \mbox{for }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}\left(e^{-1/x}\right)=e^{-1/x}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $L(n,i)$
\end_inset

 are the Lah numbers.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-1/x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}$
\end_inset

 are well defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{n}}{dx^{n}}\left(e^{-1/x}\right)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to0$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-1/x}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 much faster than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}(-1)^{n+i}\frac{L(n,i)}{x^{n+i}}$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

).
 So this function is clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, the Taylor series of this function at the origin is
 identically zero in any neighborhood of the origin since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{n}f}{dx^{n}}(0)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 cannot be equal to its Taylor series and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is not real-analytic at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Taylor's Theorem with Remainder
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function need not be equal to its Taylor series, there is a Taylor's theorem
 with remainder for 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions that is often good enough for our purposes.
 We say that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
star-shaped
\series default
 with respect to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, the line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The line segment from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is parametrized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma(t)=(1-t)p+tx$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is star-shaped with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-t)p+tx$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Taylor's theorem with remainder).
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 star-shaped with respect to a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Then there are functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(x),\dots,g_{n}(x)\in C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\qquad g_{i}(p)=\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The idea behind this proof is to differentiate and integrate the function
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p+t(x-p))$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is star-shaped with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

 the line segment 
\begin_inset Formula $p+t(x-p)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq t\leq1$
\end_inset

, lies in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p+t(x-p))$
\end_inset

 is defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq t\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 By the chain rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{df}{dt}(p+t(x-p)) & =\frac{df}{dt}(p_{1}+t(x_{1}-p_{1}),\dots,p_{n}+t(x_{n}-p_{n}))\\
 & =(\partial_{x_{1}}f)(p+t(x-p))\partial_{t}(p_{1}+t(x_{1}-p_{1}))+\cdots+(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(p+t(x-p))\partial_{t}(p_{n}+t(x_{n}-p_{n}))\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p)).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we integrate both sides with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(p+t(x-p))|_{0}^{1}=\sum(x_{i}-p_{i})\int_{0}^{1}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p))dt\label{eq:inteq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(x)=\int_{0}^{1}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p+t(x-p))dt$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We want to apply this proof to the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
e^{-1/x} & \mbox{for }x>0\\
0 & \mbox{for }x\leq0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=\int_{0}^{1}\frac{df}{dx}(p+t(x-p))dt$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
g(x) & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{df}{dx}(tx)dt\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\frac{-e^{-1/tx}}{tx^{2}}dt\\
 & =\frac{e^{-1/tx}}{x}|_{0}^{1}\\
 & =\frac{e^{-1/x}}{x}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(0)+x\left(\frac{e^{-1/x}}{x}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tangent Vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as Derivations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In elementary calculus we normally represent a vector at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 algebraically as a column of numbers
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v=\begin{pmatrix}v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
v_{3}
\end{pmatrix},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or geometrically as an arrow emanating from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is tangent to a surface in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 if it lies in the tangent plane at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Such a definition of a tangent vector to a surface presupposes that the
 surface is embedded in a Euclidean space, and so would not apply to the
 projective plane, for example, which does not sit inside an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 in any natural way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Directional Derivative
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(p_{1},\dots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a point with direction 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The line through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the direction 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 can be parametized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell:=(\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{n}):\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(t):=p+tv=(p_{1}+tv_{1},\dots,p_{i}+tv_{i},\dots,p_{n}+tv_{n})=:(\ell_{1}(t),\dots,\ell_{i}(t),\dots,\ell_{n}(t)).
\]

\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 be a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
directional derivative
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is defined to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{v}f & :=\lim_{t\to0}\left(\frac{f(\ell(t))-f(p)}{t}\right)\\
 & =\partial_{t}f(\ell(t))|_{t=0}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\partial_{x_{i}}f(\ell(0))\cdot\partial_{t}\ell_{i}(0)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

, it is understood that the partial derivatives are to be evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is a vector at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

 is a number, not a function.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{v}=\sum v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for the map that sends a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to the number 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}f$
\end_inset

.
 To simplify the notation we often omit the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 if it is clear from the context.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Germs of Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Consider the set of all pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function.
 We introduce a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 and say that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

 if there is an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subset U\cap V$
\end_inset

 containing 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

 when restricted to 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that this is an equivalence relation by showing it
 is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
 The equivalence class of 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
germ 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 for the set of all germs of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 What happens if we weaken the relation a bit? Say 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})\sim(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we no longer have an equivalence relation.
 The reason is because this relation is not transitive: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})\sim(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2},U_{2})\sim(f_{3},U_{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=f_{3}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\cap U_{3}$
\end_inset

, but this merely implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{3}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cap U_{2}\cap U_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\frac{1}{1-x}
\]

\end_inset

with domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\setminus\{1\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x)=1+x+x^{2}+x^{3}+\cdots
\]

\end_inset

with domain the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

 have the same germ at any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the open interval 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1,1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The addition and multiplication of functions induce corresponding operations
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 making it into an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},U_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2},U_{2})$
\end_inset

 be two representatives.
 Then multiplication is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1},U_{1})\cdot(f_{2},U_{2})=(f_{1}f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2}).
\]

\end_inset

We need to check that this is well-defined, so let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}',U_{1}')$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2}',U_{2}')$
\end_inset

 be two different represenatives respectively.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}=f_{1}'\text{ on }W_{1}\subset U_{1}\cap U_{1}'\text{ and }f_{2}=f_{2}'\text{ on }W_{2}\subset U_{2}\cap U_{2}'
\]

\end_inset

 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}f_{2}=f_{1}'f_{2}'\text{ on }W_{1}\cap W_{2}\subset U_{1}\cap U_{2},
\]

\end_inset

and thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1}f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2})\sim(f_{1}'f_{2}',U_{1}\cap U_{2})
\]

\end_inset

and hence this is well-defined.
 Similarly, addition is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1},U_{1})+(f_{2},U_{2})=(f_{1}+f_{2},U_{1}\cap U_{2}).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This example requires some knowledge of Algebraic Geometry.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine algebraic set over an algebraically closed field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $R=A(X)$
\end_inset

 be its coordinate ring, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 be the maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 given by the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in R$
\end_inset

 which vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 There are two equivalent ways to define the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

One way is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 to be the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 Elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

 are equivalence classes of elements of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 if there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $h\notin\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(g_{2}f_{1}-g_{1}f_{2})=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The other way is to define 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 to be the ring of all germs of polynomial functions defined on a neighborhood
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polynomial function defined on a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We can think of 
\begin_inset Formula $f/g$
\end_inset

 here as being the germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f/g,D(g))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all points such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Two such polynomial functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 (or germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}/g_{1},D(g_{1}))$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 (or germ 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{2}/g_{2},D(g_{2})$
\end_inset

) represent the same germ if they agree on some small neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 A small open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the Zariski topology is simply something of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $D(h)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 does not vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}=f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $D(h)\cap D(g_{1})\cap D(g_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 Another way of saying this is 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}g_{2}h(f_{1}/g_{1}-f_{2}/g_{2})=0$
\end_inset

 as a function on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

; this matches precisely the criterion for 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}/g_{2}$
\end_inset

 to be equal in the local ring 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\mathfrak{m}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Derivations at a Point
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 gives a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed we just need to check that it is well-defined: suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,U)\sim(g,V)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f|_{W}=g|_{W}$
\end_inset

 for some open set 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq U\cap V$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{f(p_{1},\dots,p_{i}+h,\dots,p_{n})}{h}=\lim_{h\to0}\frac{g(p_{1},\dots,p_{i}+h,\dots,p_{n})}{h}=\partial_{x_{i}}g(p).
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

, which implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{v}f & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}g(p)\\
 & =D_{v}g.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}:C_{p}^{\infty}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a well-defined map.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear and satisfies the Leibniz rule
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D_{v}(fg)=(D_{v}f)g(p)+f(p)D_{v}g,\label{eq:leibnizrule}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

precisely because the partial derivatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}$
\end_inset

 have these properties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In general, any linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $D:C_{p}^{\infty}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 satisfying the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 
\series default
or a 
\series bold
point-derivation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the set of all derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 This set is in fact a real vector space, since the sum of two derivations
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and a scalar multiplication of a derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are again derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Thus far, we know that directional derivatives at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 are all derivations at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, so there is a map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi:T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\to\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),
\]

\end_inset

where a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is mapped to the point-derivation 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 is clearly linear in 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

, the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a linear map of vector spaces.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaconstantfunctions}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is a point-derivation of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D(c)=0$
\end_inset

 for any constant function 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linearity, 
\begin_inset Formula $D(c)=cD(1)$
\end_inset

, so it suffices to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)=0$
\end_inset

.
 By the the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(1)=D(1\cdot1)=D(1)\cdot1+1\cdot D(1)=2D(1).
\]

\end_inset

Substracting 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)$
\end_inset

 from both sides gives 
\begin_inset Formula $D(1)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The 
\series bold
Kronecker delta 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is a useful notation that we frequently call upon: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{j}^{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }i=j.\\
0 & \text{if }i\neq j.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi:T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})\to\mathcal{D}_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 defined above is an isomorphism of vector spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To prove injectivity, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(v_{1},\dots,v_{n})\in T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{v}$
\end_inset

 to the coordinate function 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =D_{v}x_{j}\\
 & =\sum_{i}v_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}x_{j}\mid_{p}\\
 & =v_{j}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To prove surjectivity, let 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 be a derivation at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f,V)$
\end_inset

 be a representative of a germ in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 Making 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 smaller if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is an open ball, hence star-shaped.
 By Taylor's theorem with remainder, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}(p)=\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)$
\end_inset

.
 Applying 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 to both sides and noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $Df(p)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(p_{i})=0$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaconstantfunctions})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we get by the Leibniz rule 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:leibnizrule})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Df & =D(f(p)+\sum_{i=1}^{n}(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x))\\
 & =D(f(p))+\sum_{i=1}^{n}D\left((x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D\left((x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(x)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(D(x_{i}-p_{i})g_{i}(p)+(p_{i}-p_{i})Dg_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}(D(x_{i})-D(p_{i}))g_{i}(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D(x_{i})g_{i}(p)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}D(x_{i})\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $D=D_{v}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $v=(Dx_{1},\dots,Dx_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Vector Fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
vector field 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a function that assigns to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 has basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\partial_{x_{i}}|_{p}\}$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(p)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}(p)\partial_{x_{i}}(p),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}(p)\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

, where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are now functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We say that a vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if the coefficient functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have the vector field
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=\frac{-y}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\partial_{x}+\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}}\partial_{y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
On 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, we have the vector field 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}=x\partial_{x}-y\partial_{y}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is commonly denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 Multiplication of vector fields by functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is defined pointwise:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f\vec{v})(p)=f(p)\vec{v}(p).
\]

\end_inset

Clearly if 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}f\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}
\]

\end_inset

is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the set of all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector fields on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Vec}(U)$
\end_inset

, is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

-module.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector Fields as Derivations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, we define a new function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\vec{v}f)(p)=\vec{v}(p)f
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\vec{v}f)(p)=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}(p)\partial_{x_{i}}f(p)
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}f=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\vec{v}_{i}\partial_{x_{i}}f$
\end_inset

, which shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 function on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 gives rise to an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{\infty}(U)\to C^{\infty}(U),\qquad f\mapsto\vec{v}f.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Leibniz rule for a vector field) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 functions on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(fg)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Leibniz rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(fg)=(\vec{v}f)g+f(\vec{v}g).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 At each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}(p)$
\end_inset

 satisfies the Leibniz rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(p)(fg)=\vec{v}(p)(f)\cdot g(p)+f(p)\cdot\vec{v}(p)(g),
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 varies over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

, this becomes an inequality of functions: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}(fg)=(\vec{v}f)g+f(\vec{v}g).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is an algebra over a field 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, a 
\series bold
derivation 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-linear map 
\begin_inset Formula $D:A\to A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D(ab)=(Da)b+a(Db),
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in A$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all derivations of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed under addition and scalar multiplication and forms a vector space,
 denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Der}(A)$
\end_inset

.
 As noted above, a 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 vector field on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 gives rise to a derivation of the algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 We therefore have a map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:\text{Vec}(U)\to\text{Der}(C^{\infty}(U)),\qquad\vec{v}\mapsto(f\mapsto\vec{v}f).
\]

\end_inset

Just as the tangent vectors at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 can be identified with the point-derivations of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{p}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

, so the vector fields on an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 can be identified with the derivations of the algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}(U)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism of vector spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Exterior Algebra of Multicovectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The basic principle of manifold theory is the linearization principle, according
 to which every manifold can be locally approximated by its tangent space
 at a point, a linear object.
 In this way linear algebra enters into manifold theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Instead of working with tangent vectors, it turns out to be more fruitful
 to adopt the dual point of view and work with linear functions on a tangent
 space.
 After all, there is only so much that one can do with tangent vectors,
 which are essentially arrows, but functions, far more flexible, can be
 added, multiplied, and composed with other maps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dual Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 be two 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector spaces.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Hom}_{\mathbb{R}}(V,W)$
\end_inset

 the vector space of all linear maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:V\to W$
\end_inset

.
 Define the 
\series bold
dual space
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 to be the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Hom}_{\mathbb{R}}(V,\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
covectors
\series default
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
covectors 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite dimensional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then every 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

 can be uniquely expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 be the linear function that picks out the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th coordinate, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}(v)=v_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is characterized by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{e}_{i}(e_{j})=\delta_{j}^{i}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{for }i=j,\\
0 & \mbox{for }i\neq j.
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 form a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}$
\end_inset

 span 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(v) & =\ell\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}e_{i}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}v_{i}\ell(e_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\underline{e}_{i}(v)\ell(e_{i})\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}(v)\\
 & =\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}\right)(v)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\ell(e_{i})\underline{e}_{i}\in\mbox{Span}(\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\})$
\end_inset

.
 Next we show the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}c_{i}\underline{e}_{i}=0,\label{eq:linearindependence}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 By applying 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 to both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

equation~(
\backslash
ref{eq:linearindependence})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
dual basis 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a finite-dimensional vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Ker}(\ell)$
\end_inset

 is a hyperplane in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{e_{1},\dots,e_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\underline{e}_{1},\dots,\underline{e}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be its dual basis.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 in terms of the dual basis:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell=\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}\underline{e}_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 A vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}e_{i}$
\end_inset

 belongs to the kernel of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}a_{i}=0.$
\end_inset

 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Ker}(\ell)=V\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}X_{i}\right)=\left\{ (x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}\mid\sum_{i=1}^{n}a_{i}x_{i}=0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\in V^{\lor}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}\text{Ker}(\ell_{i})\right)=n-k.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell_{1},\dots,\ell_{k}\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent.
 We may assume that we are working in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{R}^{n})^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{i}=\underline{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}\text{Ker}(\ell_{i})\right) & =\text{dim}\left(\bigcap_{1\leq i\leq k}V\left(X_{i}\right)\right)\\
 & =\text{dim}\left(V\left(X_{1},\dots,X_{k}\right)\right)\\
 & =n-k.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The converse is trivial.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential Forms on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
cotangent space 
\series default
to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

 is defined to be the dual space 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n}))^{\lor}$
\end_inset

 of the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{p}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

.
 In parallel with the definition of a vector field, a 
\series bold
covector field 
\series default
or 
\series bold
differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form 
\series default
on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 that assigns to each point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 a covector 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}\in T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega:U\to\bigcup_{p\in U}T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n}),\qquad p\mapsto\omega_{p}\in T_{p}^{*}(\mathbb{R}^{n}).
\]

\end_inset

We call a differential 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

-form a 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset


\series bold
-form 
\series default
for short.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Jacobian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},\dots,f_{m}):U\subset\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth map from an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
Jacobian 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p):=\begin{pmatrix}(\partial_{x_{1}}f_{1})(p) & \cdots & (\partial_{x_{n}}f_{1})(p)\\
\vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
(\partial_{x_{1}}f_{m})(p) & \cdots & (\partial_{x_{n}}f_{m})(p)
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

The Jacobian satisfies the following property: for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\|f(p+\varepsilon)-f(p)-J(f)(p)(\varepsilon)\|}{\|\varepsilon\|}\to0
\]

\end_inset

as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 One can view the Jacobian as a smooth linear map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p)=(J(f)(p)_{1},\dots,J(f)(p)_{m}):\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m},
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th component 
\begin_inset Formula $J(f)(p)_{i}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(p)_{i}(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})=\sum_{j=1}^{n}(\partial_{x_{j}}f_{i})(p)x_{j}.
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $m=n$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to itself and the Jacobian matrix is a square matrix.
 In particular, we can compute its determinant, known as the 
\series bold
Jacobian determinant
\series default
.
 The Jacobian determinant at a given point gives important information about
 the behavior of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 near that point.
 For instance, the inverse function theorem tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is invertible near a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 if and only if the Jacobian determinant is non-zero.
 Furthermore, if the Jacobian determinant at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is positive, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 preserves orientation near 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},f_{2}):U\subset\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}\mid xy\in(-\pi/2,\pi/2)\text{ and }x+y\in(0,\infty)\}$
\end_inset

 and where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(x,y)=\tan(xy)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(x,y)=\ln(x+y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in U$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}y_{0}\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0}) & x_{0}\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0})\\
\frac{1}{x_{0}+y_{0}} & \frac{1}{x_{0}+y_{0}}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

The Jacobian determinant is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{det}\left(J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})\right)=\frac{(y_{0}-x_{0})\sec^{2}(x_{0}y_{0})}{x_{0}+y_{0}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,y)=x^{2}+xy+y$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}2x_{0}+y_{0}\\
x_{0}+1
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1},y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}) & =(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})^{2}+(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2})\\
 & =x_{0}^{2}+x_{0}y_{0}+y_{0}+(2x_{0}+y_{0})\varepsilon_{1}+(x_{0}+1)\varepsilon_{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}\varepsilon_{2}\\
 & =f(x_{0},y_{0})+J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})(\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2})+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}\varepsilon_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},f_{2}):\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}(x,y)=x^{2}y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(x,y)=y^{2}+x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The Jacobian of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},y_{0})\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})=\begin{pmatrix}2x_{0}y_{0} & x_{0}^{2}\\
1 & 2y_{0}
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1},y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}) & =((x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1})^{2}(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}),(y_{0}+\varepsilon_{2}^{2})+(x_{0}+\varepsilon_{1}))\\
 & =(x_{0}^{2}y_{0},y_{0}^{2}+x_{0})+(2x_{0}y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}+x_{0}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{1}+2y_{0}\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{2}^{2})\\
 & =f(x_{0},y_{0})+J(f)(x_{0},y_{0})(\varepsilon_{1},\varepsilon_{2})+(y_{0}\varepsilon_{1}^{2}+\varepsilon_{1}^{2}\varepsilon_{2},\varepsilon_{2}^{2})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U\subset\mathbb{R}^{m}\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be a smooth map from an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(p+\varepsilon)=f(p)+J(f)_{p}(\varepsilon)+\psi(\varepsilon),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is a smooth map such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\psi(\varepsilon)\|/\|\varepsilon\|\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:U\to\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(\varepsilon):=f(p+\varepsilon)-f(p)-J(f)_{p}(\varepsilon).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

